<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-formation-of-quadratic-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Formation of Quadratic Equations</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_0bb1lx08">
            <p xml:id="auto_s1afvspi">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_gh3zlstr">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_tfvohx0k">
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_x1xlgnen">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_2mh93up7">
                        1.3 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lpih6uvz">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4gw6gs7e">
                        Form quadratic equations in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uwsu226r" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_lo7mq1eh">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yt98ekf5" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_fo1k63ws">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5zhb5agz" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_0gffk89m"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_glvbgetl">
                        <p xml:id="auto_69rge68p">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that quadratic equations can be formed from given roots using the zero product property, and recognize the relationship between factors and roots.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xoinz5op">
                        <p xml:id="auto_6tp2q7yr">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Form quadratic equations from given roots or expressions using factorisation methods, including common factor extraction and grouping.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ixh6w8bj">
                        <p xml:id="auto_72cdiu2o">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply the formation of quadratic equations to model real-world situations and verify solutions by expansion.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_u22r4emk">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/formation-of-quadratic-equations.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_e9gp4azr">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/step-by-step-guide_formation-of-quadratic-equations.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_qpgimzqd">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_k7yhl46f">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8p8r82xv">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_nletjfi2">
                    Root to Equation Challenge: To explore how quadratic equations can be formed from given roots.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_tgcv850p">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ul47s6zv">
                    Groups work through three steps:
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_rphp052u">Form a quadratic equation from given roots.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_drpz626w">Write the equation in factorised form.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_y81oumxe">Swap with another group, solve the equation and find the roots.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_5p2dhjw5">
                    Sample roots for groups:
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_0cds89f0">Group 1: <m>x = 2</m> and <m>x = 3</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_qnzon2lk">Group 2: <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 4</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_03eyypxs">Group 3: <m>x = 0</m> and <m>x = 5</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_8whe4ytf">Group 4: <m>x = -2</m> and <m>x = -3</m></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_i28ufiqd">
                    Discussion prompts:
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_dqebdfc4">How did you find the quadratic equation from the roots?</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_c1w6fpuh">What did you learn about factorisation from this exercise?</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_loo4cgmf">Did you notice any patterns when forming quadratic equations?</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_aig6nx6m">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_55e4rnas">
                    Groups share their methods with the class. The teacher guides learners toward the key idea: if <m>x = p</m> and <m>x = q</m> are roots, then <m>(x - p)(x - q) = 0</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_a9gzgulh">
        <p xml:id="auto_j7ejpyzu">
            <em><term>Work in Groups.</term></em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hngn0oxq">
            <ol xml:id="auto_4x2a3sz3">
                <li xml:id="auto_668bwrmd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_b2o3nefj">Start by forming a quadratic equation using given roots.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qrcovqfr">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ldun0q39">Write your equation in factorized form.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0tmnjek7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_e2ivlgzy">Swap your equation with another group, solve it and find the roots.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ii6ebr6j">
            After completing the task, discuss these questions with the class:
            <ul xml:id="auto_xrun45m0">
                <li xml:id="auto_kdtezp5b">
                    <p xml:id="auto_s2klhwqz">How did you find the quadratic equation from the roots?</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_phmnsv37">
                    <p xml:id="auto_vadi0z3n">What did you learn about factorization from this exercise?</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_51f0r78c">
                    <p xml:id="auto_wehl8xhn">Did you notice any patterns when forming quadratic equations?</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_37l8juyn">
            Finally, each group will share their quadratic equation and the method used with the class.
        </p>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_kcu4anhy">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_wnxfdwap">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_qk2afwc5">
                <title>Key Concepts</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_g6w7xytz">
                    <alert>Quadratic Equation:</alert> Any equation of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> where <m>a, b, c</m> are constants and <m>a \neq 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_tih2eyb2">
                    <alert>Factorised Form:</alert> <m>(x + p)(x + q) = 0</m> where <m>p \times q = c</m> and <m>p + q = b</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_4x3gls3n">
                    <alert>Zero Product Property:</alert> If <m>(x + p)(x + q) = 0</m>, then <m>x = -p</m> or <m>x = -q</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_fbx8x7fi">
                    <alert>Forming Equations from Roots:</alert> If the roots are <m>x = r</m> and <m>x = s</m>, then the factors are <m>(x - r)</m> and <m>(x - s)</m>, giving the equation <m>(x - r)(x - s) = 0</m>, which expands to <m>x^2 - (r + s)x + rs = 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_cz63acpd">
                    <alert>Factoring Methods:</alert>
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_0n2pu8xp">If <m>a = 1</m>: find two numbers that multiply to <m>c</m> and add to <m>b</m>.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_w9k7umr3">If <m>a \neq 1</m>: use the ac-method (find two numbers that multiply to <m>a \times c</m> and add to <m>b</m>).</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_8fxhsfmp">Always check for common factors first (e.g., <m>6x^2 + 12x = 6x(x + 2)</m>).</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_3qj2ihme">
                    <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> <q>The equation must equal zero! Always rearrange to <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> before factorising.</q>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_6imf64pr">
        Any equation of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> where <m>a, b \, \text{and} \, c</m> are constants and <m>a \neq 0</m> is known as a quadratic equation. 
        In this section, solutions of quadratic equations using the factor method is discussed.
    </p>

    <p xml:id="auto_vfxbtcgk">
        To solve a quadratic equation by factorisation, we aim to rewrite the quadratic equation in the form of:
        <md>
            <mrow>(x+p)(x+q) \amp = 0 </mrow>
        </md>
        where <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are numbers that, when multiplied, give the product <m>c</m> (the constant term), 
        and when added, give the sum <m>b</m> (the coefficient of the middle term).
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_7zkyi955">
        To solve a quadratic eaquation, first ensure the equations is in the form;
        <me>
            ax^2 + bx + c = 0.
        </me>
        if not in the form rearrange, so that all terms are on one side of the equation and the equation equals zero.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_5487gymw">
        Factor the quadratic expression:
        <ul xml:id="auto_ecnmjfre">
            <li xml:id="auto_7cqo1odg">
                <p xml:id="auto_timwzqvu">
                    Look for two numbers that when multiplied give <m>a \times c</m> (the coefficient of <m>x^2</m>)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_l0vhy3wq">
                <p xml:id="auto_e24zrfqs">
                    And, when added give <m>b</m> (the coefficient of the middle term).
                    <ul xml:id="auto_rjd7483v">
                        <li xml:id="auto_rwmc3atg">
                            <p xml:id="auto_skqwu6qm">
                                If the quadratic has a leading coefficient <m>a = 1</m>, 
                                you only need to find two numbers that multiply to <m>c</m> and add to <m>b</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_so6kljkq">
                            <p xml:id="auto_4c7gctf6">
                                If <m>a \neq 1</m>, find two numbers that multiply to <m>a \times c</m> and add to <m>b</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_9bunswjl">
        Rewrite the middle term using these two numbers and factor by grouping, which you will have a quadratic of the form:
        <me>
            (x+p)(x+q) = 0
        </me>
    </p>

    <insight xml:id="auto_5qy96168">
        <p xml:id="auto_8qm7a5o9">
           <alert>What is a Quadratic Equation? </alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_njfaywuc">
            Any equation of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> where a, b, and c are constants and <m>a \neq 0</m> is known as a
            quadratic equation.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ivmm4o1k">
            <alert>The Factorised Form:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vsho78e0">
            To solve or form a quadratic equation by factorisation, we aim to write it in the form:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_kplj9dk6">
            <md>
                <mrow>(x+p)(x+q) \amp = 0 </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_iquosjgr">
            Where p and q are numbers that:
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_5bt58m1c">When multiplied, give the product <m>ac</m> (the constant term)</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6zev15tf">When added, give the sum <m>b</m> (the coefficient of the middle term)</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ukunzcrs">
            <alert>The Zero Product Property:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_l0b71ef0">
            If <m>(x + p)(x + q) = 0</m>, then either:
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_l2sy1a1r"><m>x + p = 0 \rightarrow  x =- p</m></li>
                OR
                <li xml:id="auto_rmu0d9os"><m>x + q = 0 \rightarrow x = - q</m></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1bkvmuxl">
           <alert>Forming Equations from Roots:</alert> 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_60hc8wy1">
            If the roots are x = r and x = s, then:
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_2aadv393">The factors are <m>(x - r) and (x - s)</m></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qfgftxmo">The equation is (x - r)(x - s) = 0</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_o2jw5b9s">Expanded: <m>x^2 - (r + s)x + rs = 0</m></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dvwu60m6">
           <alert>Factoring Methods: </alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ki96417k">
            Depending on the coefficients, you may need to:
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_3rcyucsd">Find two numbers that multiply to <m>c</m> and add to <m>b</m> (if <m>a = 1</m>)</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tdbv8su0">Find two numbers that multiply to <m>a \times c</m> and add to <m>b</m>, then factor by grouping (if <m>a \neq 1</m>)</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8vr3mnar">Always check for common factors first (e.g., <m>6x^2 + 12x = 6x(x + 2)</m>)</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_sv9ikk4x">
            <alert>Remember:</alert> The equation must equal zero! Always rearrange to get <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>before factorising
        </p>
        
    </insight>


    <!--Examples-->
    <example xml:id="auto_sb6n3xk7">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_tpnaqkzu">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_wqypz0w5">
                Solve
                <me>
                    x^2 + 6x + 8 = 0
                </me>                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_4xn4po6l">
                Factoring the left hand side (L.H.S) of the equation.
                <me>
                    x^2 + 6x + 8 = 0
                </me>
                The factors are <m>2 \, \text {and} 4</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_kan7fsni">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp x^2 + 2x + 4x + 8 = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                Now create common factors
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp x(x + 2) + 4(x + 2) = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                Grouping them together we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp (x + 2) + (x + 4) = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_8k8lvq98">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_g82zpv2x">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_udxeg2vv">
                <title>Worked Example</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_0drypre9">
                    Form a quadratic equation from <m>6x^2 + 12x</m>:
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_lct75hx5">Set the expression equal to zero: <m>6x^2 + 12x = 0</m>.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_rixvnl0u">Identify the common factor <m>6x</m>.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_o0cpa4g5">Factor: <m>6x(x + 2) = 0</m>.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_n66f9jlb">Find roots: <m>x = 0</m> or <m>x = -2</m>.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_yd5579jb">Verification: <m>6x(x + 2) = 6x^2 + 12x \checkmark</m>.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_93cklmp5">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_rjjzo8iw">
                    Emphasise the importance of setting the expression equal to zero and identifying common factors before attempting other factorisation methods.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

     <example xml:id="auto_pzjprar4">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_g2r79gss">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vgy01h7a">
                Form a quadratic expression using the factoring method.
                <me>
                    6x^2 + 12x
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_46cf4vpg">
                To form a quadratic expression using the factoring method, first set the expression equal to <m>0</m> to form a quadratic equation:
                <md>
                    <mrow> 6x^2 + 12x \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hlojg6xz">
                Remove the common factor out and form a bracket:
                <md>
                    <mrow>6x(x + 2) \amp = 0</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_rtylv1hr">
                Thus, the factored form of expression <m>6x^2 + 12x</m> is;
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vgkf92ti">
               <md>
                <mrow>6x(x + 2) \amp = 0 </mrow>
               </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>

